 without making consoles or arcade cabinets), in 1979"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"024d41f0-ea27-424b-8c2e-9e9f00af0e4b","name":"core/list-item","attributes":{"content":"The introduction to the United States of Japan’s hugely popular \u003cem\u003ePac-Man\u003c/em\u003e"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"936a7432-5d17-42d5-b322-6dc8c7f9d5aa","name":"core/list-item","attributes":{"content":"Nintendo’s creation of \u003cem\u003eDonkey Kong\u003c/em\u003e, which introduced the world to the character Mario"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"cfa32da6-8f6a-4098-974a-40fb39eb623e","name":"core/list-item","attributes":{"content":"Microsoft’s release of its first \u003cem\u003eFlight\u003c/em\u003e Simulator game"},"innerBlocks":[]}]},{"clientId":"5afa39cd-5f73-463a-aa60-2e7b42363d25","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The Video Game Crash ","level":2,"id":"the-video-game-crash"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"069dc3d4-18f5-41d5-8fdc-845bdb0d9104","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"In 1983, the North American video game industry experienced a major “crash” due to a number of factors, including an oversaturated game console market, competition from computer gaming, and a surplus of over-hyped, low-quality games, such as the infamous \u003cem\u003eE.T.\u003c/em\u003e, an Atari game based on the eponymous movie and often considered the worst game ever created.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"77a2d44f-a077-4bbf-982f-ed7caa22ff04","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Lasting a couple of years, the crash led to the bankruptcy of several home computer and video game console companies.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"90736aff-3c50-424a-95d9-743803178c2c","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The video game home industry began to recover in 1985 when the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES), called Famicom in Japan, came to the United States. The NES had improved 8-bit graphics, colors, sound and gameplay over previous consoles.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"f9bc344a-f582-43b4-9b50-99a33cf1b7fa","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Nintendo, a Japanese company that began as a playing card manufacturer in 1889, released a number of important video game franchises still around today, such as \u003cem\u003eSuper Mario Bros.\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem\u003eThe Legend of Zelda\u003c/em\u003e, and \u003cem\u003eMetroid\u003c/em\u003e.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"5df28b73-0803-462a-b80f-555a2d35e510","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Additionally, Nintendo imposed various regulations on third-party games developed for its system, helping to combat rushed, low-quality software. Third-party developers released many other long-lasting franchises, such as Capcom’s \u003cem\u003eMega Man\u003c/em\u003e, Konami’s \u003cem\u003eCastlevania\u003c/em\u003e, Square’s Final Fantasy, and Enix’s \u003cem\u003eDragon Quest\u003c/em\u003e (Square and Enix would later merge to form Square Enix in 2003).","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"2fac93e2-4004-44c2-b638-7f9d133fd4e7","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"In 1989, Nintendo made waves again by popularizing handheld gaming with the release of its 8-bit Game Boy video game device and the often-bundled game \u003cem\u003eTetris\u003c/em\u003e. Over the next 25 years, Nintendo would release a number of successful successors to the Game Boy, including the Game Boy color in 1998, Nintendo DS in 2004, and Nintendo 3DS in 2011.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"702c835a-0e27-4fb8-aa82-96ef43cad475","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The First Console War ","level":2,"id":"the-first-console-war"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"d0fcb21a-5e40-4739-96f7-0a8e75fc0f23","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Also in 1989, Sega released its 16-bit Genesis console in North America as a successor to its 1986 Sega Master Sys