ef7-b739-63515a0bf8c1","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"With a much larger library of games, lower price point, and successful marketing, the Genesis had leapfrogged ahead of the SNES in North America by this time. But Sega was unable to find similar success in Japan. ","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"023724fd-d36c-4136-a1d7-6198e1fa568f","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The Rise of 3D Gaming ","level":2,"id":"the-rise-of-3d-gaming"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"9912f630-67db-4643-afc9-3a770b0265e7","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"With a leap in computer technology, the fifth generation of video games ushered in the three-dimensional era of gaming.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"defc2b5f-ad2f-43b0-bf63-058c462a93f9","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"In 1995, Sega released in North America its Saturn system, the first 32-bit console that played games on CDs rather than cartridges, five months ahead of schedule. This move was to beat Sony’s first foray into video games, the Playstation, which sold for $100 less than the Saturn when it launched later that year. The following year, Nintendo released its cartridge-based 64-bit system, the Nintendo 64.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"5cb7a05d-1c12-4791-860d-07ddba876ac2","name":"corpnews-blocks/featured-content","attributes":{"id":34514,"featured_media":34515,"title":"5 of the Most Influential Early Video Games","excerpt":"Home video games may seem like a contemporary phenomenon, but they actually have roots that go back to the Truman administration. That’s when computer scientists began tinkering with electronic machines to construct basic automated games, such as the pioneering “Bertie the Brain,” an ingenious 13-foot-tall, tic-tac-toe-playing computer showcased at a Canadian national exposition in 1950. […]","slug":"top-early-home-video-games-pong-pacman","featured_media_url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2022/10/b1c204-2.jpg?width=1024\u0026height=577","type":"story"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"c554c963-2622-419d-9c64-462a3fe3a8b2","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Though Sega and Nintendo each released their fair share of highly-rated, on-brand 3D titles, such as \u003cem\u003eVirtua Fighter\u003c/em\u003e on the Saturn and \u003cem\u003eSuper Mario 64\u003c/em\u003e on the Nintendo 64, the established video game companies couldn’t compete with Sony’s strong third-party support, which helped the Playstation secure numerous exclusive titles.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"0c48e4fd-e2c1-47ca-9410-34f49d82d9c0","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Simply put: Sony dominated the video game market and would continue to do so into the next generation. In fact, the Playstation 2, released in 2000 and able to play original Playstation games, would become the best-selling game console of all time.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"dee14a4b-58dc-4516-aa0d-2878cc4522d5","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The Playstation 2, which was the first console that used DVDs, went up against the Sega Dreamcast (released in 1999), the Nintendo Gamecube (2001), and \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/microsoft-releases-xbox-gaming-console\"\u003eMicrosoft’s Xbox\u003c/a\u003e (2001).","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"396d81be-e108-424a-8bda-5e603840818f","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The Dreamcast—considered by many to be ahead of its time and one of the greatest consoles ever made for several reasons, including its capability for online gaming—was a commercial flop that ended Sega’s console efforts. Sega pulled the plug on the system in 2001, becoming a third-party software company henceforth. ","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"2f0f73e7-736a-4876-9fd2-fe0c4ccd16e2","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Modern Age of 